<subSubSection pageId="135" pageNumber="136" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="135.[151,1436,1306,2015]" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">
DIAGNOSIS: 
<emphasis box="[330,457,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Male adult</emphasis>
: unknown. 
<emphasis box="[601,756,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Female adult</emphasis>
: only extant species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1030,1165,1307,1332]" class="Insecta" family="Corethrellidae" genus="Corethrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="135" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1030,1165,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Corethrella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the New World with a distinct midlength wing band and with extensive dark scales basal to the midlength band but without any of these on the anal vein (Fig. 70G), with a dark brown thorax (
<figureCitation box="[882,991,1386,1412]" captionStart="FIGURE 52" captionStartId="358.[151,255,2017,2041]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,209,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-29@358.[192,1395,197,1990]" captionTargetPageId="358" captionText="FIGURE 52. Thoraces and legs of female Corethrella, lateral view." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 52C</figureCitation>
), dark brown midfemur, base of hind tibia darkly pigmented (contrasting with pale apex of hind femur), hind femur with basal 0.6 darkly pigmented (
<figureCitation box="[253,361,1466,1492]" captionStart="FIGURE 52" captionStartId="358.[151,255,2017,2041]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,209,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-29@358.[192,1395,197,1990]" captionTargetPageId="358" captionText="FIGURE 52. Thoraces and legs of female Corethrella, lateral view." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 52C</figureCitation>
), and all femora with slender scales.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="136" lastPageNumber="137" pageId="135" pageNumber="136" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="135.[151,1436,1306,2015]" lastBlockId="136.[151,1436,152,978]" lastPageId="136" lastPageNumber="137" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">
DESCRIPTION: 
<emphasis box="[415,545,1507,1532]" italics="true" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Male adult</emphasis>
. Unknown. 
<emphasis box="[695,852,1507,1532]" italics="true" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Female adult</emphasis>
. Descriptive statistics: see 
<tableCitation box="[1190,1337,1506,1532]" captionStart-0="TABLE 6" captionStart-1="TABLE 7" captionStart-2="TABLE 8" captionStart-3="TABLE 9" captionStart-4="TABLE 10" captionStart-5="TABLE 11" captionStartId-0="277.[151,241,153,177]" captionStartId-1="280.[151,241,153,177]" captionStartId-2="283.[151,241,153,177]" captionStartId-3="286.[151,241,151,175]" captionStartId-4="289.[151,239,153,177]" captionStartId-5="292.[151,241,153,177]" captionText-0="TABLE 6. Length of wing of females of species of Corethrella. Values are in mm." captionText-1="TABLE 7. Ratio of length of R1/wing length of females of species of Corethrella." captionText-2="TABLE 8. Ratio of head capsule width/height of females of species of Corethrella." captionText-3="TABLE 9. Number of setae on the clypeus of females of species of Corethrella. The number does not include those" captionText-4="TABLE 10. Number of posterior anepisternal setae of females of species of Corethrella." captionText-5="TABLE 11. Number of anepimeral setae of females of species of Corethrella." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Tables 6–11</tableCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1361,1428,1506,1532]" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Head</emphasis>
: Outline in anterior view laterally elongate (
<figureCitation box="[657,752,1546,1572]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="317.[151,255,1927,1951]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,197,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-23@317.[177,1410,197,1900]" captionTargetPageId="317" captionText="FIGURE 11. Head capsules of female Corethrella, anterior view." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 11I</figureCitation>
). Coronal suture short, extending ventrally about midway along area between ommatidia (as in 
<figureCitation box="[615,723,1586,1612]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="322.[151,255,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,349,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-31@322.[177,1411,197,1921]" captionTargetPageId="322" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dorsal portion of head capsules of female Corethrella, anterior view." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 16F</figureCitation>
). Two large setae on frons between ventromedial area of ommatida (as in 
<figureCitation box="[351,455,1626,1652]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="322.[151,255,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,349,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-31@322.[177,1411,197,1921]" captionTargetPageId="322" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dorsal portion of head capsules of female Corethrella, anterior view." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 16F</figureCitation>
). Antennal flagellomeres 1–6 light brown, 7–13 somewhat darker; pedicel with at least one distinctive, more elongate, stout, dorsal or dorsolateral seta; flagellomeres as in 
<figureCitation box="[1228,1333,1666,1692]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="336.[151,255,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[187,1396,238,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-25@336.[177,1411,197,1921]" captionTargetPageId="336" captionText="FIGURE 30. Antennae of female Corethrella." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 30E</figureCitation>
, sensilla coeloconica distributed as in 
<tableCitation box="[497,585,1706,1732]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="265.[151,241,151,175]" captionText="TABLE 1. Pattern of sensilla coeloconica (= s.c.) on antennal flagellomeres of species of Corethrella. Numbers refer to the flagellomere with sensilla coeloconica, with those in brackets referring to flagellomeres with or without sensilla coeloconica. Mis. (missing) refers to damaged specimens, unknown refers to missing stages, uncertain refers to specimens in which visibility was too poor to be certain of whether sensilla coeloconica were present or not. Those species names with a “†” are those of fossils. Corethrella librata, known only as immature stages, is not included." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Table 1</tableCitation>
; flagellomere 13 with well-developed apical bifurcation. Clypeus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="324.[151,255,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,299,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-33@324.[177,1411,197,1921]" captionTargetPageId="324" captionText="FIGURE 18. Clypei of female Corethrella. Lateral setae, even if present, are not shown." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 18P</figureCitation>
) wide. Mandible with small, pointed teeth. Palpus (
<figureCitation box="[826,911,1746,1772]" captionStart="FIGURE 34" captionStartId="340.[151,255,1947,1971]" captionText="FIGURE 34. Right palpi of female Corethrella." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
AB) pale; segment 3 swollen apically. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Thorax</emphasis>
(as in 
<figureCitation box="[276,385,1786,1812]" captionStart="FIGURE 52" captionStartId="358.[151,255,2017,2041]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,209,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-29@358.[192,1395,197,1990]" captionTargetPageId="358" captionText="FIGURE 52. Thoraces and legs of female Corethrella, lateral view." pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Fig. 52C</figureCitation>
): Dark brown, pale sclerites around base of wing. Posterior portion of dorsocentral row with group of about 8 elongate setae. Prescutal suture short, not extending more than half way to dorsocentral row of setae. Anterior anepisternum divided diagonally by sinuous suture, dorsal portion about equal to ventral portion. Ventral portion of posterior anepisternum triangular, uniformly brown, with anterodorsal margin thick. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[235,303,1946,1972]" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">Wing</emphasis>
(Fig. 70G): Apex of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[590,598,1963,1977]" fontSize="6" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">2</subScript>
basal to apex of M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[833,841,1963,1977]" fontSize="6" pageId="135" pageNumber="136">1</subScript>
. Anterior margin with differently, discretely pigmented scales (indicating anterior margin of midlength band), with basal/subbasal band extending from C to CuA (no dark scales on A), with midlength band; veins (other than costa and wing margin) with well-developed scales. Halter as dark as scutellum. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[667,726,191,217]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Legs</emphasis>
(as in 
<figureCitation box="[812,922,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURE 52" captionStartId="358.[151,255,2017,2041]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,209,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-29@358.[192,1395,197,1990]" captionTargetPageId="358" captionText="FIGURE 52. Thoraces and legs of female Corethrella, lateral view." pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Fig. 52C</figureCitation>
): Dark brown with knees of fore-, midlegs pale, basal 0.6 of hind femur dark, hind tibia medium brown with non-discrete dark apical pigmentation. Femora, tibiae with slender scales (also some in patch of whip-like setae on posterior portion of hind tibia). Midleg with thick, subapical setae on each of at least tarsomeres 1–3. Claws of each leg equal to those of others; equal on each leg, simple (without inner teeth). Empodia slender. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[977,1099,351,377]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Dark brown, with segments 8–9 darker. Cercus dark brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="136.[151,1436,152,978]" box="[198,467,432,458]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis box="[198,322,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Immatures</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="136" pageNumber="137" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="136.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">
DISTRIBUTION AND BIONOMICS: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Borkent" authorityYear="2008" box="[677,878,472,497]" class="Insecta" family="Corethrellidae" genus="Corethrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirta">
<emphasis box="[677,878,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Corethrella hirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1180,1230,472,498]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry name="Costa Rica" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(Fig. 119A) at an altitude of 
<specimenCount box="[543,609,512,538]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" type="generic">
<quantity box="[543,604,512,538]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" unit="m" value="40.0">40 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Adults were collected with a frog-call trap, using the call of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Le Conte" authorityYear="1856" class="Amphibia" family="Hylidae" genus="Hyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gratiosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Hyla gratiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, placed at the edge of the “frog ponds” just south of the River Station. The species was not common in the otherwise abundant samples of other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[752,887,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Corethrellidae" genus="Corethrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[752,887,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Corethrella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected at this site on 
<date box="[1168,1372,592,618]" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" value="2004-03-01" valueMax="2004-03-02" valueMin="2004-03-01">March 1–2, 2004</date>
. The serrate mandibles of the female adults and their attraction to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Le Conte" authorityYear="1856" box="[860,1022,632,657]" class="Amphibia" family="Hylidae" genus="Hyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gratiosa">
<emphasis box="[860,1022,632,657]" italics="true" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">Hyla gratiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
calls suggest that they feed on frog blood in nature. Female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Borkent" authorityYear="2008" box="[454,548,672,697]" class="Insecta" family="Corethrellidae" genus="Corethrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="136" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirta">
<emphasis box="[454,548,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="136" pageNumber="137">C. hirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique in the family, however, in having the bifid apex of the labrum splayed anterolaterally. These mouthpart modifications suggest that females feed in a distinctive manner or on a distinctive host.
</paragraph>
